  "prompt": "I scored 336 in GRE along with 5.0 in analytical writing. My grade is just around 8.0. Which universities should I focus on?",
  "response": "A GRE score of 336 (out of 340) and a 5.0 in Analytical Writing is an **excellent achievement** and puts you in a highly competitive position for top universities worldwide. With a GPA of around 8.0 (on a 10-point scale), your academic profile is strong, though GPA expectations vary by program and university. Here\u2019s how to approach your university selection:\n\n---\n\n### **Factors to Consider**\n1. **Program and Field of Study**: Universities prioritize programs differently. Research programs that align with your academic and career goals.\n2. **GRE and GPA Expectations**: While your GRE score is exceptional, some top-tier universities may have higher GPA expectations (e.g., 8.5+). However, your GRE can offset a slightly lower GPA.\n3. **Research vs. Coursework**: If you\u2019re applying for research-based programs (MS/PhD), your research experience, publications, and SOP will carry significant weight.\n4. **University Ranking and Fit**: Focus on universities that are strong in your field, not just overall rankings.\n5. **Location and Funding**: Consider the country, cost of attendance, and scholarship opportunities.\n\n---\n\n### **University Suggestions**\nBased on your profile, here are some suggestions for competitive universities across different tiers:\n\n#### **Tier 1: Top Global Universities (Highly Competitive)**\n- **United States**:\n  - Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT)\n  - Stanford University\n  - University of California, Berkeley (UCB)\n  - California Institute of Technology (Caltech)\n  - Harvard University\n  - Princeton University\n  - Carnegie Mellon University (CMU)\n- **United Kingdom**:\n  - University of Oxford\n  - University of Cambridge\n  - Imperial College London\n  - University College London (UCL)\n- **Canada**:\n  - University of Toronto\n  - University of British Columbia (UBC)\n  - McGill University\n- **Europe**:\n  - ETH Zurich (Switzerland)\n  - Technical University of Munich (Germany)\n\n#### **Tier 2: Strong Universities (Moderately Competitive)**\n- **United States**:\n  - University of Texas at Austin\n  - University of Michigan, Ann Arbor\n  - University of Wisconsin-Madison\n  - University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign (UIUC)\n  - Georgia Institute of Technology\n- **United Kingdom**:\n  - University of Edinburgh\n  - King\u2019s College London\n  - University of Manchester\n- **Canada**:\n  - University of Waterloo\n  - McGill University\n  - University of Alberta\n- **Australia**:\n  - Australian National University (ANU)\n  - University of Melbourne\n  - University of Sydney\n\n#### **Tier 3: Good Universities (Target/Safety)**\n- **United States**:\n  - University of Florida\n  - Ohio State University\n  - University of Pittsburgh\n  - Arizona State University (ASU)\n- **United Kingdom**:\n  - University of Warwick\n  - University of Bristol\n  - University of Glasgow\n- **Canada**:\n  - University of Calgary\n  - Simon Fraser University (SFU)\n  - University of Ottawa\n\n---\n\n### **Next Steps**\n1. **Research Programs**: Identify universities that align with your goals and check their GRE and GPA requirements.\n2. **Strengthen Your Profile**: Highlight research experience, internships, and relevant projects in your SOP and resume.\n3. **Letters of Recommendation**: Secure strong LORs from professors or employers who can vouch for your abilities.\n4. **Application Strategy**: Apply to 6\u201310 universities, with a mix of reach, target, and safety schools.\n\nWith your GRE score, you\u2019re well-positioned for top-tier programs. Focus on presenting a cohesive application to maximize your chances!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
